Prosper Loan Data Analysis¶

by Youssef Kamal¶

Investigation Overview¶

This Investigation walks through Loan Prosper Dataset. It aims to have a basic analysis of this dataset nature, what trends are there, what features are more important, and which give more info about Loan Status. There're many different visualizations to look at things more throughly. Finally, a summary of what've been collected.

Dataset Overview¶

This Dataset is US Loan Prosper Dataset. There're many features, among which a few are selected for this investigation. This dataset is from Aug 2009 to March 2014. It has 100k+ records, covering most Occupations, states, Interest rates, etc.

Index¶

  • Preliminary Wrangling
  • Univariate Exploration
  • Bivariate Exploration
  • Multivariate Exploration
  • Summary

def labelingh(ax, s = 13, w_=1.05, y_=0.5):
    for p in ax.patches:
        width = p.get_width()
        x, y = p.get_xy()
        ax.annotate(f'{width:.0f}', (width*w_, y+y_), fontsize=s, va='center')

def labelingv(ax, s = 13, h_=1.05, x_=0.5):
    for p in ax.patches:
        height = p.get_height()
        x, y = p.get_xy()
        ax.annotate(f'{height:.0f}', (x+x_, height*h_), fontsize=s, ha='center')
        
def rand_jitter(arr, f=.01):
    stdev = f*(max(arr)-min(arr))
    return arr + np.random.randn(len(arr)) * stdev

_ = [[1*10**x,3*10**x] for x in range(5)]
log_ticks = [i for j in _ for i in j]
_ = [['%ik'%(1*10**x),'%ik'%(3*10**x)] for x in range(2)]
log_labels = [0,3,10,30,100,300]+[i for j in _ for i in j]

color = sb.color_palette()[0]

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

LoanStatus object Occupation object EmploymentStatus object BorrowerState object IncomeRange object LoanOriginationDate object BorrowerAPR float64 BorrowerRate float64 ProsperRating float64 DebtToIncomeRatio float64 MonthlyLoanPayment float64 Term int64 LoanOriginalAmount int64 Recommendations int64 IsBorrowerHomeowner bool IncomeVerifiable bool

The data initially had 100k+ rows and 80 rows, so a subset of the data is chosen to work on, and the features of interest. The new clean data is saved in another file to upload along with source code.

The cleaning steps taken have changed the results slightly from what's expected if we used the full data, but still in our investigation and limited scope, the differences will be rather tolerable.

There're records among those contain null in some feature that have some distinct characteristics that don't share with other, and as I've eliminated rows with null values, the sample no matter how big will most likely not explain the whole and actual population, so it'd seem like sample isn't truly random. This is for clarification, as for solution it'd require to have in-depth investigation, which is probably beyond scope.

There're some categorical features, stated below in detail:

LoanStatus : Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue, Cancelled. Last category might not appear in a small sample, as it's occurances are low.

Occupation : Among many jobs' values stated in this field, Most common is Other and Professional, there's some analysis about 'Other' against other jobs.

EmploymentStatus : Employed, Full-time, Other, Part-time, Retired, Self-employed. Sorted in decreasing order, having Employed as most common entry.

BorrowerState : There's data for 48 state in the sample, that might not include all states in the dataset, but that means other states have little to no help to analysis, at least on a small scale, having 'CA' as most common states.

IncomeRange : Not employed, \$1-24,999, \\$25,000-49,999, \$50,000-74,999, \\$75,000-99,999, \$100,000+. There's another Range '\\$0' which is mostly like Not employed, again its effect isn't worrisome.

There's one Datetime col, Loan Origination Date, on format 'yyyy-mm-dd'.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

In this invistigation, main features are that give valuable info or trends, that might include the following features: LoanStatus, BorrowerAPR, BorrowerRate, LoanOriginalAmount.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

There're a few features that to look into, starting with univariate exploration and through the end to get valuable info from a multivariate plot. It's not quite the case that everyone has some background about finance and how loans work, and so for me, so there're few features that collectively, supposedly, will give more details and clear the way for through investigation.
Occupation, EmploymentStatus, BorrowerState, IncomeRange, BorrowerAPR, BorrowerRate, DebtToIncomeRatio, IsBorrowerHomeowner, IncomeVerifiable; these features will give some info about the borrowers and how capable are they to clear their debts. Along with LoanStatus, ProsperRating, MonthlyLoanPayment, Term, LoanOriginalAmount, Recommendations.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There're some features that have un balanced distribution over categories, os it might be insihtful to take a look at the log-transform. APR and Rate both have peaks that preceded immediatley by a fall, it would suggest that some percantages have advantages or they're standard. Same with LoanOriginalAmount, there were some amounts that were rarely requested, so they had shorter spikes that others, so log-transform on y-scale would make them more clear to see. Same with LoanStatus and BorrowerState.

DebtToIncomeRatio plot is right-skewed, where there's a long tail towrads positive end, so x-lim along with log-transform would make it more apparent.

In [1173]:
def dfBi(x, y):
    dfBi = df.groupby([x,y]).count().iloc[:,0].unstack()
    if y == 'LoanStatus':
        PastDue = dfBi.iloc[:,-6:].sum(axis=1)
        PastDue.name = 'PastDue'
        drop_cols = [col for col in dfBi.iloc[0,:].keys() if 'Past Due' in col]
        dfBi.drop(drop_cols, axis=1, inplace=True)
        dfBi['PastDue'] = PastDue
    _x = df[x].value_counts()
    _x_ = _x.keys()
    for c in _x_:
        dfBi.loc[c] = dfBi.loc[c]/_x[c]
    return _x, dfBi

What factors affect a loan’s outcome status?¶

Through the last few viusaliztions, we've seen plots depicting some point about Loan status. It's certainly not the whole story, but from this simple analysis it's possible to conclude some facts, or relations. Though, these relations are linear relations or seemingly intuitive.

Borrower APR/Rate for better results, likely to be at +ve ~0.2 - ~0.3, the better the worse likely, with some exceptions.
Debt/Income ratio, also for better results likely to be +ve ~0.2 or lower, with some positive results at lower ~0.
HomeOwners are likely to have better results, or the least not for worst.

Through this exploration, there's been visualizations discuss Loan Status. This one above depicts Loan Original Money vs Loan Status, it's not clear if there's really some amount that acts as a threshold on either sides. It make sense there's wide range of borrowers from different classes, so it'd be better to visualize how it looke like for different Income Range and different Loan Status distirbution of Loan Original Amount, which is a multivariate plot. Also, Income Range vs Loan Original Amount shows that, indeed, borrowers with higher level income originate loans with higher amount, which is only possible with their high Income that make Debt/Income ratio lower, which is safety sign for lenders. Aside from this we saw that Loan Orignal Amount has as distribution full of spikes. That being said, the trend we see, give an indication that people needs' are growing or, on general, people imporving their income , or maybe, inflation.
